fields.Description/Abstract:
&lt;p&gt;Empathizing with how someone from a historically marginalized population might feel when the&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;criminal justice system unfairly targets them can be challenging for many students. To an extent,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;the lack of such lived experiences can be mitigated through extended or virtual reality techniques&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;in criminal justice classrooms (e.g., Smith, 2021). In this study, we utilize the Empathy Lens, a&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;360-degree, extended reality (XR) video through which the participants experience the point of&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;view of another individual. More specifically, the study explores the impact of XR on student&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;empathy and opinions surrounding a police-citizen encounter where the perspectives of&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;individuals from different racial and ethnic backgrounds are presented. The sample includes&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;students from three course sections of an undergraduate policing course at a minority-serving&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Western university. Students view a police-citizen encounter through virtual reality headsets,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;allowing them to view the encounter from the perspective of a police officer and a detained&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;civilian. Reflections of this experience served as the qualitative data source. Our findings&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;demonstrate the XR technology's ability to challenge students to consider multiple perspectives&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;and their sense of empathy in high-stress situations. Practical recommendations, limitations, and&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;suggestions for future directions in criminal justice pedagogy are discussed.&lt;/p&gt;
